    • DEFAULT

      static final int DEFAULT
      No special options set. Since: 2.74
      See Also:
      • Constant Field Values

    • ANCHORED

      static final int ANCHORED
      The pattern is forced to be "anchored", that is,
      it is constrained to match only at the first matching point in the
      string that is being searched. This effect can also be achieved by
      appropriate constructs in the pattern itself such as the "^"
      metacharacter.
      See Also:
      • Constant Field Values

    • NOTBOL

      static final int NOTBOL
      Specifies that first character of the string is
      not the beginning of a line, so the circumflex metacharacter should
      not match before it. Setting this without %G_REGEX_MULTILINE (at
      compile time) causes circumflex never to match. This option affects
      only the behaviour of the circumflex metacharacter, it does not
      affect "\A".
      See Also:
      • Constant Field Values

    • NOTEOL

      static final int NOTEOL
      Specifies that the end of the subject string is
      not the end of a line, so the dollar metacharacter should not match
      it nor (except in multiline mode) a newline immediately before it.
      Setting this without %G_REGEX_MULTILINE (at compile time) causes
      dollar never to match. This option affects only the behaviour of
      the dollar metacharacter, it does not affect "\Z" or "\z".
      See Also:
      • Constant Field Values

    • NOTEMPTY

      static final int NOTEMPTY
      An empty string is not considered to be a valid
      match if this option is set. If there are alternatives in the pattern,
      they are tried. If all the alternatives match the empty string, the
      entire match fails. For example, if the pattern "a?b?" is applied to
      a string not beginning with "a" or "b", it matches the empty string
      at the start of the string. With this flag set, this match is not
      valid, so GRegex searches further into the string for occurrences
      of "a" or "b".
      See Also:

    • NEWLINE_ANY

      static final int NEWLINE_ANY
      Overrides the newline definition set when
      creating a new #GRegex, any Unicode newline sequence
      is recognised as a newline. These are '\r', '\n' and '\rn', and the
      single characters U+000B LINE TABULATION, U+000C FORM FEED (FF),
      U+0085 NEXT LINE (NEL), U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and
      U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR.
      See Also:

      is recognized as a newline. Since: 2.34
      See Also:

      static final int BSR_ANY
      Overrides the newline definition for "\R" set when
      creating a new #GRegex; any Unicode newline character or character sequence
      are recognized as a newline by "\R". These are '\r', '\n' and '\rn', and the
      single characters U+000B LINE TABULATION, U+000C FORM FEED (FF),
      U+0085 NEXT LINE (NEL), U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and
      U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR. Since: 2.34

    • PARTIAL_HARD

      static final int PARTIAL_HARD
      Turns on the partial matching feature. In contrast to
      to %G_REGEX_MATCH_PARTIAL_SOFT, this stops matching as soon as a partial match
      is found, without continuing to search for a possible complete match. See
      g_match_info_is_partial_match() for more information. Since: 2.34
      See Also:
      • Constant Field Values

    • NOTEMPTY_ATSTART

      static final int NOTEMPTY_ATSTART
      Like %G_REGEX_MATCH_NOTEMPTY, but only applied to
      the start of the matched string. For anchored
      patterns this can only happen for pattern containing "\K". Since: 2.34
      See Also:
